Using [`Collectors.toList()`][1] you can get what you want to do:

    import java.util.stream.*
    
    class Item {
        final String name
        
        Item(name) {
            this.name = name
        }
        
        @Override
        String toString() {
            name
        }
    }
    
    def itemize(String name) {
        Optional.of(new Item(name))
    }
    
    
    def finalCollection = [ &#39;some&#39;, &#39;items&#39;, &#39;really&#39;, &#39;not&#39;, &#39;important&#39; ].stream()
            .map { itemize(it) } //map String to Optional&lt;Item&gt;
            .flatMap { it.map(Stream.&amp;of).orElseGet(Stream.&amp;empty) } //convert to Stream&lt;Item&gt;
            .collect (Collectors.toList()) 
    
    assert &#39;java.util.ArrayList&#39; == finalCollection.class.name        
    assert finalCollection.collect { it.name } == [&#39;some&#39;, &#39;items&#39;, &#39;really&#39;, &#39;not&#39;, &#39;important&#39;]

Anyway, with groovy 2.4.5 the above is working also with

    def finalCollection = [ &#39;some&#39;, &#39;items&#39;, &#39;really&#39;, &#39;not&#39;, &#39;important&#39; ].stream()
            .map { itemize(it) } //map String to Optional&lt;Item&gt;
            .flatMap { it.map(Stream.&amp;of).orElseGet(Stream.&amp;empty) } //convert to Stream&lt;Item&gt;
            .collect()

that uses [groovy&#39;s collect][2]:

&gt; transforming each item into a new value using Closure.IDENTITY as a
&gt; transformer, basically returning a list of items copied from the
&gt; original object.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Collectors.html#toList--
  [2]: http://docs.groovy-lang.org/latest/html/api/org/codehaus/groovy/runtime/DefaultGroovyMethods.html#collect(java.lang.Object)

Groovy 2.5.0 and above adds [`toList`][1] and [`toSet`][2] methods as [enhancements to Stream][3]. No need to use  `Collectors.toList()` anymore.

    def finalCollection = [ &#39;some&#39;, &#39;items&#39;, &#39;really&#39;, &#39;not&#39;, &#39;important&#39; ].stream()
            .map { it }
            .flatMap { it.map(Stream.&amp;of).orElseGet(Stream.&amp;empty) }
            .toList()


  [1]: https://docs.groovy-lang.org/latest/html/groovy-jdk/java/util/stream/Stream.html#toList()
  [2]: https://docs.groovy-lang.org/latest/html/groovy-jdk/java/util/stream/Stream.html#toSet()
  [3]: https://docs.groovy-lang.org/latest/html/groovy-jdk/java/util/stream/Stream.html

On my side, I found a solution to use Java Stream, Collectors in Groovy Scripts.

By casting the parameter of collect. It forces the usage of `Stream.collect()` instead of Groovy&#39;s collect()

``` lang-java
import java.util.stream.Collector
import java.util.stream.Collectors;
//...
List&lt;String&gt; stringsAsList = [&quot;aa&quot;,&quot;bbb&quot;];
return stringsAsList.stream().collect((Collector)Collectors.joining(&quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;, &quot;&quot;));
```

After add guava dependency (not the latest version), the error is resolved. 

    &lt;dependency&gt;
       &lt;groupId&gt;com.google.guava&lt;/groupId&gt;
       &lt;artifactId&gt;guava&lt;/artifactId&gt;
       &lt;version&gt;31.1-jre&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;

